commentBody:
@Steve 
Nope.  I'm saying that picking a name (let alone a weird spelling) from a book/movie that many haven't seen, and that would be obscure even for many who had, pretty much walks past "unfair".  There's no way that that society/whatever name could be picked up from the zeitgeist.  He's just a hardcore fan.

What was Turner's first name?  Badge number?

@Mark P 

Do you have nary a care or hardly a care? What if you could care less or couldn’t care less?

English is weird.

@Rich in Atlanta 
Watch that ducking and running business, my brother!  we're not as flexible as we used to be!
Left you a note in my comment (above somewhere)!

@Barry Ancona 
TIL learned that "Cream Ale" wasn't a prorietary marketing gimmick by Genesee. Thank you, BA!






PBR for the emus.

@Susan E 

Plus of course, despite not having either egg or cream in it, the egg cream is still a dairy item. 

Chocolate syrup, seltzer and of course MiLK!

@Janine 
I also had a typo I couldn't find for the longest time, "this is jeoparty",  why I thought the phrase ended in 'party'?  An error from an early guess that I failed to catch.  

It was a decent puzzle.  I thought for a good while I might actually get by without any cheats, but the upper right corner got me.  Still, two cheats isn't bad, for me, anyway!

@MOL
Hippo Birdy 2 Ewe


And to appease the gatekeepers let's pretend the birdy is an EMU, even though it's not.

@Prof. Toru Tanaka 

I'm not a big snacker, but my favorite -- guilty pleasure, yes I have a favorite potato chip! -- is Utz's Crab Chip. The name is a little misleading because it's all about the Old Bay seasoning -- no shellfish involved.

While fairly ubiquitous in Maryland, these chips are a rarer find north of the Mid-Atlantic... and thus I have the perfect excuse to purchase them whenever they cross my path! 🦀

@Earthling 

Very strong challenge to the puzzle.   Probably the best one 
I've seen yet.

@Nancy
No reason to necessarily remember that UTZ has been in the puzzle before.  It could have easily been gotten on the crosses other times, hence forgettable.  (However the other chips are Lay's not Lay.)
UTZ potato chips can be found in NYC and if you like potato chips you should give them a try. They are good.  They were the potato chip of choice when growing up  on LI.

@dave 

The “core tenet” you’re referring to is that a word cannot be in the clue for its own entry. There’s no rule that says it can’t be elsewhere in the puzzle. 

This is a common misconception.

@Howard 

That momentarily threw me until I realized that you need to read “Old dating initials” as “Dating initials for things that are old.”

I think I would have preferred “Dating initials for questions in the NYT Flashback quiz that Eric Hougland usually gets wrong.”

@Malcolm 

I definitely hear you and have been there before. And I definitely fall into three of your categories of knowledge gaps with today's puzzle. (I have watched Black Panther but I still didn't get it immediately.)

However, I've learned DEKE and ELIHU (sometimes ELI) from doing puzzles, so that made the crossings work out for me. I don't know how often those two show up but I have them added to my mental list of crossword words to remember. I've only been doing puzzles for a little over 10 months so it helps me to identify those items that I find (or read here) are recurrent.

@Amy Yes, but the word should be "Feint" not "Faint"

I'm sure Barry Ancona will disagree but "Faint" means soft or light.  

"Feint" means phony.

@Thomas Clark 
I believe it means nice but unenthusiastic praise, not phony, and the correct word is faint. 
Feint is a mock blow or attack.

@B 
Oh, thought @Michael had written that the theme itself "never came to be".

Oops.  ;)
